[00:00.40]	[The palace.,]
[00:01.20]	[Enter the DUCHESS OF YORK, with the two children of CLARENCE]
[00:02.00]Boy	Tell me, good grandam, is our father dead?
[00:05.07]DUCHESS OF YORK	No, boy.
[00:05.94]Boy	Why do you wring your hands, and beat your breast,
[00:09.61]	And cry 'O Clarence, my unhappy son!'
[00:12.28]Girl	Why do you look on us, and shake your head,
[00:15.49]	And call us wretches, orphans, castaways
[00:18.49]	If that our noble father be alive?
[00:21.16]DUCHESS OF YORK	My pretty cousins, you mistake me much;
[00:24.10]	I do lament the sickness of the king.
[00:26.97]	As loath to lose him, not your father's death;
[00:30.37]	It were lost sorrow to wail one that's lost.
[00:33.71]Boy	Then, grandam, you conclude that he is dead.
[00:36.92]	The king my uncle is to blame for this:
[00:39.92]	God will revenge it; whom I will importune
[00:43.13]	With daily prayers all to that effect.
[00:46.06]Girl	And so will I.
[00:47.40]DUCHESS OF YORK	Peace, children, peace! the king doth love you well:
[00:51.07]	Incapable and shallow innocents,
[00:53.61]	You cannot guess who caused your father's death.
[00:57.22]Boy	Grandam, we can; for my good uncle Gloucester
[01:00.55]	Told me, the king, provoked by the queen,
[01:03.56]	Devised impeachments to imprison him :
